Use ASP.NET Core's **`WebApplicationFactory<T>`** — it hosts your app in-memory and gives you an `HttpClient` without opening a real port. Wire that client into the MCP C# SDK's transport layer.

Here's the pattern:

```csharp
// 1. Add these packages to your test project:
//    Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing
//    ModelContextProtocol  (the C# MCP SDK)

// 2. Create a test fixture
public class McpIntegrationTests : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly WebApplicationFactory<Program> _factory;

    public McpIntegrationTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
    {
        _factory = factory;
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task CallTool_ReturnsExpectedResult()
    {
        // WebApplicationFactory gives you an HttpClient
        // backed by an in-memory test server — no real port needed.
        var httpClient = _factory.CreateClient();

        // Use SseClientTransport (for SSE-based MCP servers)
        // or StreamableHttpClientTransport (for Streamable HTTP).
        // Pass your test HttpClient so it routes to the in-memory host.
        var transport = new SseClientTransport(new SseClientTransportOptions
        {
            Endpoint = new Uri(httpClient.BaseAddress!, "/sse"),
            Name = "test-client"
        }, httpClient);

        // For Streamable HTTP instead:
        // var transport = new StreamableHttpClientTransport(
        //     new StreamableHttpClientTransportOptions
        //     {
        //         Endpoint = new Uri(httpClient.BaseAddress!, "/mcp"),
        //         Name = "test-client"
        //     }, httpClient);

        await using var client = await McpClientFactory.CreateAsync(transport);

        // Now test your tools/prompts/resources:
        var result = await client.CallToolAsync("my-tool", new { input = "hello" });

        Assert.NotNull(result);
        Assert.Contains(result.Content, c => c.Text!.Contains("expected output"));
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`WebApplicationFactory<Program>`** hosts your real `Program` startup in-process — middleware, DI, routing all run exactly as in production.
- The `HttpClient` from `CreateClient()` talks to that in-memory server; pass it to the MCP SDK transport so all MCP protocol traffic stays in-process.
- Use **`SseClientTransport`** if your server uses the SSE transport, or **`StreamableHttpClientTransport`** for the newer Streamable HTTP transport.
- Override services for testing via `_factory.WithWebHostBuilder(b => b.ConfigureServices(...))` as you would in any ASP.NET Core integration test.
- Make sure `Program` is accessible (add `public partial class Program { }` at the bottom of your entry point if needed, or use `[assembly: InternalsVisibleTo("YourTestProject")]`).
